#1
top_names <- babynames |>
  filter(year >= 1990, sex == "F", 
         grepl("^La", name, ignore.case = TRUE) | grepl("ana$", name, ignore.case = TRUE)) |>
  group_by(year, name) |>
  summarise(count = sum(n), .groups = 'drop') |>
  arrange(year, desc(count)) |>
  group_by(year) |>
  slice_max(count, n = 5)
print(top_names)
## # A tibble: 140 × 3
## # Groups:   year [28]

# Plotting
ggplot(top_names, aes(x = year, y = count, color = name)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(title = "Top 5 Popular Female Names Starting with 'La' or Ending with 'ana' (1990+)",
       x = "Year", y = "Number of Babies")

# 2

#5 
# Find the most popular names in 1950 for each sex
popular_1950 <- babynames |>
  filter(year == 1950) |>
  group_by(sex) |>
  slice_max(order_by = n, n = 1) |>
  select(sex, name, n)

# Extract the names from popular_1950
popular_1950_names <- popular_1950$name

# Find counts of these names in 2015
counts_2015 <- babynames %>%
  filter(year == 2015, grepl(paste0("^(", paste(popular_1950_names, collapse = "|"), ")$"), name)) %>%
  select(sex, name, n)

# Display the result
counts_2015
## # A tibble: 3 × 3
##   sex   name      n
##   <chr> <chr> <int>
## 1 F     Linda   425
## 2 F     James    39
## 3 M     James 14799
#6
name_regex <- paste0("^(", paste(popular_1950_names, collapse = "|"), ")$")

# Filter the data from 1900 to 2015 and select the relevant columns, using `n` for the count column
popularity_trend <- babynames %>%
  filter(year >= 1900 & year <= 2015, grepl(name_regex, name)) %>%
  select(year, sex, name, n)

popularity_trend

# Create the stacked bar chart
ggplot(popularity_trend, aes(x = year, y = n, fill = name)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(
    title = "Popularity of Selected Names Over Time",
    subtitle = "The trend shows changes in the popularity of the most common names from 1950."
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.title = element_blank(), axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

#7
# List of words to check
words <- c("color", "colour", "flavor", "flavour", "gray", "grey", 
           "modeling", "modelling", "airplane", "aeroplane", 
           "center", "centre", "colouring")

# Regular expression pattern
pattern <- "\\b(?:colou?r|flavou?r|gr[aae]y|mode?l(?:ing|l)?|airplane|aeroplane|center|centre)\\b"

# Find matching words using grep
matches <- grep(pattern, words, value = TRUE)

# Output the matches
print(matches)
##  [1] "color"     "colour"    "flavor"    "flavour"   "gray"      "grey"     
##  [7] "modeling"  "airplane"  "aeroplane" "center"    "centre"
